# Actus — External Acts

> *Latin*: **actus** — "act / deed / performance of an action".
> The bridge between the user's verb (CLI argv) and the subsystems
> that carry out the deed.

## Philosophical Role

Every CLI invocation is an **external act** upon the machine. Actus is the
subsystem that receives that act, validates it at the boundary, and
dispatches it into the internal arena. Once dispatched, the act is spent;
what remains is the consequence inside Conscientia, Machina, Memoria, and
the rest.

An act is, by its nature, transient. Therefore Actus owns no long-lived
state, no classes, no singletons — only free functions in
`namespace deusridet`. The only module-scope datum is
`g_shutdown_requested`, the atomic flag that binds a running act to the
OS signal handler so the act can end gracefully when reality interrupts.

## Contract with Surrounding Subsystems

- **main.cpp** depends on Actus (argument parsing + dispatch).
- Actus depends on subsystem facades (Machina, Conscientia, Nexus, Sensus,
  Memoria, …) via their public headers only.
- Actus never depends on the implementation headers of another subsystem.
  When a current `cmd_*` reaches into private headers, that is a facade
  debt tracked in `docs/en/architecture/00-overview.md`.

## Current State (Refactor Debt)

`actus.cpp` is 2700+ lines — the last monolith of the project, well over
the R1 hard limit. The PDD refactor backlog schedules a one-file-per-command
split (Step 5) followed by facade extraction (Step 7+). No new command
should be added to `actus.cpp`; new commands belong in their own
translation units under `src/actus/`.
